<org.eclipse.epf.uma:ArtifactDescription xmi:version="2.0" xmlns:xmi="http://www.omg.org/XMI" xmlns:org.eclipse.epf.uma="http://www.eclipse.org/epf/uma/1.0.6/uma.ecore" xmlns:epf="http://www.eclipse.org/epf" epf:version="1.5.1" xmlns:rmc="http://www.ibm.com/rmc" rmc:version="7.5.1" xmi:id="-DrG78XR44--IcIBXJHxb3Q" name="technology_environment,_jSeg4DxaEdyz7ZnE62_AvQ" guid="-DrG78XR44--IcIBXJHxb3Q" changeDate="2007-08-12T07:54:45.703-0700" version="1.0.0">
  <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    This artifact provides:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        An inventory of an enterprise's installed applications, data, computing and network infrastructure, and the current&#xD;
        security architecture indicating the existing or planned security zones, secure channels, or network security zones&#xD;
        and trust levels.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The current status of all of the non-technical, management aspects of the overall technical environment, including:&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li style=&quot;LIST-STYLE-TYPE: none&quot;>&#xD;
        &lt;ul>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                The IT/IS/IT security organization(s), roles, and responsibilities&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                The existing IT strategy, policies, and plans (including skills acquisition and sourcing options)&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Security policies, standards, and processes&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Development policies and practices&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                System management policies and practices&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
        &lt;/ul>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;br />&#xD;
    These details about the technical environment are summarized into a form that can be readily used as input to many&#xD;
    future architecture, design, and infrastructure delivery and management activities, along with observations on current&#xD;
    known IT/IS deficiencies, concerns, and user satisfaction with IT.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;br />&#xD;
    It should be noted that this artifact is NOT intended for documenting the results of an assessment of the current&#xD;
    technical environment. The artifact can be restricted in scope (for example, to the part of the technical environment&#xD;
    affected by the introduction of a new package or system).&lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
  <keyConsiderations>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The following general guidance is recommended:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Aim to gather all of the inputs and information needed for a single project at the same time, regardless of the&#xD;
        artifacts that will be defined. Plan the information gathering as a joint exercise between all interested parties,&#xD;
        and agree on the tools and techniques to be used, especially as some information gathering activities will cross&#xD;
        organizational boundaries.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        When gathering environment information, go beyond the classical information and determine if any limiting&#xD;
        environmental situations exists (such as noisy plant floors, extra bright areas where it is hard to see a screen,&#xD;
        or pervasive devices with small, text-only screens).&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Verify the IT Environment by review with the client sponsor and appropriate senior executives. It may also be&#xD;
        appropriate to hold a peer and quality assurance review (a peer who has accessibility skills may be necessary in&#xD;
        complex IT situations).&lt;br />&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul></keyConsiderations>
  <purpose>&lt;p>&#xD;
    This artifact provides the basic data and information that is used to:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Provide a base point against which new initiatives (for example an IT strategy assessment, an enterprise&#xD;
        architecture engagement or development of one or more IT based business systems) can be defined&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Provide a basis for subsequent assessments of the IT environment for functional and technical quality&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Provide a basis for identifying gaps between the defined environment and future required environments&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Provide a basis for subsequent assessments of the effectiveness of:&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li style=&quot;LIST-STYLE-TYPE: none&quot;>&#xD;
        &lt;ul>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                IT management, processes, policies, and plans&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Development policies and practices&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Accessibility policies and practices&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                System management policies and practices&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Security and privacy policies and practices&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
        &lt;/ul>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Give valuable insights into possible areas of key requirements, for both technical improvements to the IT&#xD;
        infrastructure and the application portfolio.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Provide a baseline for understanding the system changes necessary for new IT-based business solutions.&lt;br />&#xD;
        These insights are key inputs to subsequent planning activities in support of strategic business directions and&#xD;
        goals.&lt;br />&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul></purpose>
  <impactOfNotHaving>&lt;p>&#xD;
    Without a comprehensive understanding of the enterprises environment, it is likely that IT strategy, IT planning,&#xD;
    architecture definition, transition planning, architecture assessment, and system and infrastructure design activities&#xD;
    will not be soundly based. In particular:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The same information will be required by different project tasks over time, and will be gathered separately and&#xD;
        repetitively.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The information will not be considered when developing alternatives and planning work, and issues will not be&#xD;
        discovered until the cost of addressing them has increased.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Interfacing and transitional issues associated with the introduction of a new package or system may be overlooked,&#xD;
        or their impact underestimated.&lt;br />&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul></impactOfNotHaving>
  <reasonsForNotNeeding>&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot; style=&quot;MARGIN: 6pt 0in&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;span style=&quot;LAYOUT-GRID-MODE: line&quot;>Potential reasons for not needing this artifact are:&lt;/span>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;div class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot; style=&quot;MARGIN: 6pt 0in&quot;>&#xD;
            &lt;span style=&quot;LAYOUT-GRID-MODE: line&quot;>There is no existing systems or IS/IT organization, or the current&#xD;
            environment can be completely disregarded (in other words, it is being replaced).&lt;/span>&#xD;
        &lt;/div>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;div class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot; style=&quot;MARGIN: 6pt 0in&quot;>&#xD;
            &lt;span style=&quot;LAYOUT-GRID-MODE: line; COLOR: black&quot;>The information has already been gathered as part of a&#xD;
            previous IT assessment activity, and it is readily available in a form suitable for use in a future assessment.&#xD;
            In this instance, time should still be allowed for reviewing the completeness of this material.&lt;/span>&#xD;
        &lt;/div>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul></reasonsForNotNeeding>
  <briefOutline>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The IT Environment typically includes the following sections:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h4>&#xD;
    Introduction&#xD;
&lt;/h4>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Describes the scope and context of the IT environment, and includes any other overview information that is of&#xD;
    relevance.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h4>&#xD;
    Hardware&#xD;
&lt;/h4>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Usually production environments, but may include development and test environments as well (if this is relevant).&#xD;
    Includes CPUs, peripherals, specialist devices (including hardware used by users who have disabilities), and&#xD;
    communications hardware.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h4>&#xD;
    Software&#xD;
&lt;/h4>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    This includes:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Technical Software: Including systems software, middleware, and systems management software&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Application Software and Databases: Including assistive technology software&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Application Development Environment: Including development, test, and run-time systems.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;h4>&#xD;
    Management Processes&#xD;
&lt;/h4>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    This includes:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        An IT organization chart, including roles and responsibilities&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        A model or list of recognized IT management and governance processes&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        High-level process diagrams (where appropriate)&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        A matrix of IT management processes and owners or participants&lt;br />&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul></briefOutline>
  <representationOptions>&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNorm al&quot; style=&quot;MARGIN: 6pt 0in&quot;>&#xD;
    The IT Environment artifact is usually produced in the form of a report, but may also be delivered in presentation&#xD;
    format, or may exist as one or more models created using a modeling tool. &#xD;
&lt;/p>&lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;h4>&#xD;
    Notation&#xD;
&lt;/h4>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The notation of the IT Environment is usually in the form of text with supporting tables and diagrams. Diagrams may be&#xD;
    informal, or created using formal modeling notations such as the Unified Modeling Language 2 (UML 2).&#xD;
&lt;/p></representationOptions>
</org.eclipse.epf.uma:ArtifactDescription>
